    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf a language server replies with a JSON-RPC response whose `id` is `null`, the rpc read loop dies:\n\n```\nvim/_core/shared.lua:0: Cannot convert vim.NIL to integer\n\t[C]: in function 'error'\n\tvim/_core/shared.lua: in function '_assert_integer'\n\t.../runtime/lua/vim/lsp/rpc.lua:435: in function 'handle_body'\n\t.../runtime/lua/vim/lsp/rpc.lua:596: in function 'handle_body'\n\t.../runtime/lua/vim/lsp/rpc.lua:246: in function ''\n```\n\n`vim.json.decode` turns JSON `null` into `vim.NIL`, and `vim.NIL` is truthy in Lua. So in `Client:handle_body` the \"this is a response\" branch passes its `decoded.id` guard and then trips on the integer assert:\n\n```lua\nelseif\n  decoded.id            -- vim.NIL, so this is truthy\n  and (\n    (decoded.error == nil and decoded.result ~= nil)\n    or (decoded.result == nil and decoded.error ~= nil and decoded.error ~= vim.NIL)\n  )\nthen\n  local result_id = vim._assert_integer(decoded.id)   -- rpc.lua:435, throws here\n```\n\n`id: null` is allowed by JSON-RPC 2.0 (a server uses it when it can't recover the request id, e.g. a parse error), so it shouldn't bring the client down.\n\nI ran into it intermittently while pasting large blocks (a burst of didChange plus the follow-up requests), but it reproduces deterministically with a stub server.\n\nFor whoever fixes this: making `_assert_integer` return `nil` isn't enough on its own, because `result_id` gets concatenated a little further down at `rpc.lua:478` (`'No callback found for server response id ' .. result_id`), so that path needs the `vim.NIL` case handled too. Normalizing `decoded.id` to `nil` right after the decode (so it falls through to the unknown-message branch) covers both spots.\n\n### Steps to reproduce using \"nvim --clean -u minimal_init.lua\"\n\nStub server that answers every request with `id: null`, save as `/tmp/fakelsp.py`:\n\n```python\nimport sys, json\n\n\ndef read_msg():\n    length = 0\n    while True:\n        line = sys.stdin.buffer.readline()\n        if not line:\n            return None\n        s = line.decode(\"ascii\", \"replace\")\n        if s == \"\\r\\n\":\n            break\n        if s.lower().startswith(\"content-length:\"):\n            length = int(s.split(\":\", 1)[1].strip())\n    return json.loads(sys.stdin.buffer.read(length))\n\n\ndef send(obj):\n    data = json.dumps(obj).encode(\"utf-8\")\n    sys.stdout.buffer.write(b\"Content-Length: %d\\r\\n\\r\\n\" % len(data))\n    sys.stdout.buffer.write(data)\n    sys.stdout.buffer.flush()\n\n\nwhile True:\n    m = read_msg()\n    if m is None:\n        break\n    if \"id\" in m:  # a request -> reply with id:null\n        result = {\"capabilities\": {}} if m.get(\"method\") == \"initialize\" else None\n        send({\"jsonrpc\": \"2.0\", \"id\": None, \"result\": result})\n```\n\n`minimal_init.lua`:\n\n```lua\nvim.lsp.start({\n  name = \"bugged-ls\",\n  cmd = { \"python3\", \"/tmp/fakelsp.py\" },\n  root_dir = \"/tmp\",\n})\n```\n\nThen:\n\n```\nnvim --clean -u minimal_init.lua\n```\n\nThe error fires as soon as the `initialize` reply (with `id: null`) is handled.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nA response with `id: null` is dropped/ignored instead of taking down the rpc read loop.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.1, Release build, LuaJIT 2.1.1774638290\n\n### Language server name/version\n\nAny server that emits `id: null` in a response. The repro uses the small python stub above, so no real server is needed.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nUbuntu 24.04.4 LTS, kernel 6.17.0\n\n### Log file\n\nn/a, it's in the client itself. Full traceback is above.\n",
